

SSL/TLS Setup on AWS

Enable HTTPS for a Custom Domain using Route 53, ACM & Application Load Balancer (ALB)


---

📌 Topic Overview

This guide explains how to secure a custom domain with HTTPS (SSL/TLS) on AWS using managed services, without installing certificates manually on EC2.


---

🔐 What is SSL/TLS (in short)?

SSL/TLS encrypts data between browser and server

Prevents man-in-the-middle attacks

Required for:

Security

SEO ranking

Modern browsers (Chrome blocks HTTP)



AWS provides free SSL certificates using ACM.


---

🔄 High-Level Workflow

Domain (Route 53)
        ↓
SSL Certificate (ACM)
        ↓
Application Load Balancer (HTTPS : 443)
        ↓
Target Group
        ↓
EC2 (Web Server)
        ↓
Browser (🔒 HTTPS)


---

Part 1: Launch & Configure EC2 Instance

🎯 Goal

Run a web application on EC2 that will receive traffic from ALB, not directly from users.


---

Step 1.1: Launch EC2

Name: web-server

AMI: Ubuntu

Instance Type: t2.micro / t3.micro

Key Pair: Select existing or create new


Network Settings

Auto-assign Public IP: ✅ Enable

Security Group:

SSH (22)

HTTP (80)

HTTPS (443)



> ⚠️ EC2 will later receive traffic only from ALB, but open rules are fine for lab/demo.




---

Step 1.2: Install Web Server & Sample Website

Connect to EC2 via SSH and run:

sudo apt update -y
sudo apt install nginx -y
sudo systemctl start nginx
sudo systemctl enable nginx

Deploy Sample Website

sudo apt install wget unzip -y
wget <link_to_zip_file>
unzip themwagon.zip

sudo rm -rf /var/www/html/*
sudo mv themwagon/* /var/www/html/

✅ Verify using EC2 Public IP (HTTP should work).


---

Part 2: Domain & Route 53 (Pre-check)

🎯 Goal

Ensure your domain is already connected to Route 53.

Domain registered via GoDaddy / Hostinger

Nameservers updated to Route 53 NS records

Hosted Zone exists in Route 53


> You may temporarily have an A record pointing to EC2 — this will be replaced later.




---

Part 3: Request SSL Certificate using ACM

🎯 Goal

Get a free, trusted SSL certificate from AWS.


---

Step 3.1: Request Certificate

1. Go to AWS Certificate Manager (ACM)


2. Click Request certificate


3. Select Public certificate



Domain Names

mywebsitedemo.com

*.mywebsitedemo.com (Wildcard)


Validation Method

✅ DNS Validation (recommended)


Click Request.


---

Step 3.2: Validate Certificate

1. Open the Pending certificate


2. Click Create records in Route 53


3. Click Create records



⏳ Wait 5–20 minutes

✅ Status changes to Issued


---

🔎 Why DNS Validation?

Automatic

No email dependency

Best practice in production



---

Part 4: Create Application Load Balancer (ALB)

🎯 Goal

Terminate SSL at ALB and forward traffic securely to EC2.


---

Step 4.1: Create Target Group

Type: Instances

Protocol: HTTP

Port: 80

Name: tg-ubuntu


Register Targets

Select EC2 instance

Include as pending

Create Target Group



---

Step 4.2: Create Load Balancer

1. Go to EC2 → Load Balancers → Create


2. Select Application Load Balancer



Configuration

Scheme: Internet-facing

VPC: Default

AZs: Select at least two

Security Group: Allow HTTP & HTTPS



---

Listeners

Listener 1 (Default)

HTTP : 80 → Forward to target group (temporary)


Listener 2 (Secure)

HTTPS : 443

SSL Certificate: Select ACM certificate

Default Action: Forward to tg-ubuntu


Create Load Balancer.


---

Part 5: HTTP → HTTPS Redirect

🎯 Goal

Force all traffic to HTTPS (security best practice).


---

Step 5.1: Modify HTTP Listener

1. Go to ALB → Listeners


2. Select HTTP : 80


3. Edit rules



Redirect Rule

Action: Redirect

Protocol: HTTPS

Port: 443

Host / Path / Query: Preserve

Status Code: 301 (Permanent)


Save changes.


---

Part 6: Update Route 53 (Domain → ALB)

🎯 Goal

Point domain to ALB (not EC2).


---

Step 6.1: Create Alias Record

1. Route 53 → Hosted Zone


2. Create / Edit A Record



Record Settings

Record Name: (blank for root domain)

Record Type: A

Alias: ✅ Yes

Route traffic to:

Application Load Balancer

Select Region

Select ALB



Create record.


---

🔑 Why Alias instead of IP?

ALB IPs change

Alias auto-updates

No cost for Route 53 alias queries



---

Part 7: Final Verification

1. Open browser


2. Visit:



http://yourdomain.com

Expected Result

Auto-redirect to https://

🔒 Padlock icon visible

Certificate issued by Amazon


🎉 HTTPS successfully enabled!


---

📌 Interview & Exam Notes

ACM certificates cannot be attached directly to EC2

SSL termination happens at ALB

Route 53 Alias works only with AWS resources

HTTP → HTTPS redirect is done at ALB listener

ACM is region-specific (must match ALB region)
